Yichun Chen MSBA Final Project: Facebook ads analysis¶

  • dataset source (downloaded from Kaggle): https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/loveall/clicks-conversion-tracking

  • In descriptic analysis, I explore which age group, gender, and interest group can generate more conversions, so that the company can target these groups when placing marketing ads on Facebook in future. I also do a correlation analysis of the numeric variables

  • In inferencial analysis, I try to find an adequate model to explain the data.

  • Dependent variable: 'Conversions': number of people who actually purchased the product.

  • Explanatory variables:
    • 'Impressions': number of times the ads were shown to facebook users.
    • 'Clicks': number of people who clicked on the ad.
    • 'Spent': amount of money spent on the ad

Findings:¶

It seems that the ads were targeted to the wrong interests groups. For example, many ads were displayed to people in interest[16],[27]and [10] , but these two interest groups' conversions were not as high as the less targeted groups: [100],[101],[104], [107] and [112].

Part 4 Conclusions:¶

  • $r^{2}$ for 5 models:
    • model 1: 0.468
    • model 2: 0.313
    • model 3: 0.352
    • model 4: 0.554
    • model 5: 0.554
  • We compared the two models with highest R squared, model 1 and model 5.
    • Based on the F test, F = 219.684184 and p value = 1.391040e-45 indicate that model1 and model5 are significantly different.
    • Since Model 5 has a higher $r^{2}$ (0.554 vs.0.468), meaning it can explain the dependence variable better.

Concluding remarks:¶

  • Age group [30-34] have more conversions than other age groups, regardless of gender.
  • Many ads were displayed to people in interest group [16],[27]and [10] , but these interest groups' conversions were not as high as the less targeted groups: [100],[101],[104], [107] and [112].
  • Correlation analysis and pairplot suggested a weak positive correlation between converions (the dependent variable) and the predictor variables: Impressions, Clicks and Spent
  • Model 5 (Impressions + Spent) is the best model, with a R squared of 0.554, meaning Impressions and Spent together can explain 55.4% variance in the sales conversions .
